{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1b20a9c8-921d-4263-910c-7a7241a7a095","content":"It works. Here's the minimal program:\n\n**PersonJson.csproj**\n```xml\n<Project Sdk=\"Microsoft.NET.Sdk\">\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n    <TargetFramework>net8.0</TargetFramework>\n    <ImplicitUsings>enable</ImplicitUsings>\n  </PropertyGroup>\n</Project>\n```\n\n**Program.cs**\n```csharp\nusing System.Text.Json;\n\nvar person = new Person(\"Jane\", 30);\nvar options = new JsonSerializerOptions { PropertyNamingPolicy = JsonNamingPolicy.CamelCase };\nConsole.WriteLine(JsonSerializer.Serialize(person, options));\n\npublic record Person(string Name, int Age);\n```\n\n**Output:** `{\"name\":\"Jane\",\"age\":30}`\n\nThe key is `JsonNamingPolicy.CamelCase` passed via `JsonSerializerOptions` — it converts PascalCase properties (`Name`, `Age`) to camelCase (`name`, `age`) during serialization.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"80e219f9-468b-4dbb-897e-78a2652aa5e8","outputTokens":258,"requestId":"1830:FBA15:30A31AE:3532BBB:69FBE219"},"id":"b4ba652f-4b7f-483a-82a2-edadde2f1585","timestamp":"2026-05-07T00:51:44.145Z","parentId":"d570dd69-2cf8-4146-8be3-bbfd1c4683f0"}
